Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-24

Title   : GST-led consumption boost: Dabur, Marico, Trent, cement names look promising: Rajesh Palviya 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-24T03:30:00
Fetched : 2025-09-24T04:51:29.375323
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/expert-view/gst-led-consumption-boost-dabur-marico-trent-cement-names-look-promising-rajesh-palviya/articleshow/124060759.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
According to him, companies such as Dabur, Marico, Trent, and select cement names stand to benefit meaningfully from the anticipated demand revival, making them promising bets for investors in the medium term. Edited Excerpts –
Kshitij Anand: Let me just get your perspective on the markets right now. For the past 12 months, Nifty and Sensex have not moved much. We are seeing flat to mildly negative returns on the headline indices. So yes, straight up, where are the markets headed? What are your chart patterns telling you?
Rajesh Palviya: It has been almost 12 months with Nifty still not able to make a new all-time high. So, this time correction as well as price correction, both we have already witnessed in this market. If we analyse historically, this is the longest time correction we are experiencing post-COVID. But yes, looking at the reforms which the government has undertaken in the last couple of months, that is now giving us confidence that Nifty is poised to again move back to the all-time high trajectory in the next couple of months. The kind of recovery we have already seen from the lower levels, the broader market is also participating in this rally. Yes, global headwinds are still disturbing the market and traders and investors are a little cautious because of the news flow coming from the global market. That is the only concern at this juncture. But otherwise, things are very well placed and we believe that once these global headwinds cool off and any arrangement between trade tariffs or whatever measures the US/Trump administration is taking at this juncture settle down at a certain level, the market is likely to make a new all-time high in the coming months.
Looking at the broader market, especially the midcap space, the kind of buying interest happening in domestically oriented sectors—stocks from real estate, BFSI, FMCG, consumption, automobiles—all this is giving a sign that yes, the market is optimistic. Once we are able to break out above 25,700, a possible target of 26,500–26,600 may be seen by December or January. On the downside, 25,000 needs to be protected. That is the important level for Nifty.
At this juncture, we are focusing more on the consumption-oriented sectors. Automobiles are clearly outperforming. The kind of buying interest we are witnessing in the two-wheeler as well as the four-wheeler space clearly shows that with the rate reductions happening in both segments, which have already been passed on to customers, demand will be boosted and we may see good traction in the automobile space. This is one sector where one can focus. On actionable points: Hero MotoCorp and Bajaj Auto are our preferred choices from the two-wheeler space, while from four-wheelers, Maruti and Mahindra & Mahindra. These four stocks from the automobile space look strong.
Again, from the real estate point of view, most stocks have already corrected. And in the last couple of weeks, many stocks are showing signs of recovery and breakouts have already taken place. Stocks like DLF and Oberoi Realty look more promising from the technical standpoint. These stocks can give good returns going forward, so one can focus on them.
Kshitij Anand: And let me get your perspective on the recent burning issue in the IT industry, which is the H-1B visas. The headline number has captured $1 lakh annual fees imposed on some of these IT companies or the persons applying for the visa. On the reaction side, we saw ADRs taking a hit and then IT stocks falling on Monday morning. For someone who holds IT stocks in their portfolio, what would be your advice? If they are already sitting on profits, should they book them? And yes, if somebody is there for the long term, should they go underweight on some of these IT players because headwinds keep mounting? We are not seeing any tailwinds for the sector. Global growth concerns were already a problem before and now the H-1B visa issue has come into play. What are your views?
Rajesh Palviya: Historically, if we look at it, IT stocks were wealth creators, but in the last couple of years these stocks have not delivered returns to investors. Even this year itself, we have seen around a 25% correction in most IT stocks. Again, a lot of headwinds are disturbing sentiment and most investors are keeping a cautious stance on IT stocks.
AI is another disruption that is making everyone question how this technology will shape up, how IT companies will evolve, and how they will gain market share in terms of business. That is one factor. Another is the new visa fee that came in this weekend. But clarity also came with this announcement that this applies to new visas. Post-COVID, we have seen most IT companies working on an offshore model. Yes, for very key projects they have to deploy manpower to the US or other countries, but most things are being done offshore.
With higher visa fees, they may try to hire resources locally—for example, IT engineers residing in the US. Or instead of offshore, they may move towards nearshoring, hiring resources from countries close to the US. This could be one change to meet the cost burden from the new visa policy.
I do not believe there will be much impact because most projects are delivered offshore and companies will try to pass this cost to the end user. In terms of profitability, I do not think there will be much impact—maybe 1% to 2% EBITDA pressure. But overall, the sector is in a downtrend and such news is again hurting investor sentiment. Investors are still not buying these stocks because clarity is lacking. Once clarity comes, once management commentaries are available in the public domain on the impact of this new visa policy and margin pressure, then those looking at a longer perspective can use this decline as a buying opportunity.
It is a core sector. Yes, there could be some pressure in terms of projects, margins, and revenues, but for a long-term perspective, if another 3-4% correction comes from these levels, it is an opportunity for those looking to deploy capital in a sector where prices are attractive and time correction has already taken place.
Kshitij Anand: So, valuations are looking attractive.
Rajesh Palviya: Yes. They can look at some of the midcap IT companies rather than largecap IT because pressure is more on the largecap IT companies as they are catering more to US projects. So, pressure would be on largecap IT companies, but companies like Coforge and Mphasis from the midcap IT universe can be considered. From largecap, yes, stocks like HCL Tech or Wipro could also look attractive.
Kshitij Anand: So, no need to panic at this point in time.
Rajesh Palviya: Yes, no need to panic.
Kshitij Anand: Now, any word on the GST names—who could be the beneficiaries? You have already covered autos in your earlier conversation, but from a consumption space as well, do you see any wealth creators in the coming few years from a three- to five-year perspective?
Rajesh Palviya: A lot of things are going to evolve post-GST because it will have a ripple effect on the economy itself. Consumption is going to remain a major theme for the next couple of months at least. So, stocks from the FMCG basket can be looked at. For example, Dabur and Marico are looking attractive. We have already witnessed a big correction in these stocks and now gradually they are showing signs of recovery. So, Dabur and Marico can be considered.
Again, some of the themes we are focusing on are new-age stocks, which can also be looked at at this juncture. Zomato and Swiggy—these two stocks are also looking very promising, and their technical structures are very strong from a short- to medium-term perspective. These two stocks can also be looked at.
Even from the consumption side, Trent is available at a very attractive price. We have already witnessed underperformance and now the stock is available at a multi-month support area. Trent can be looked at from the consumption theme, and this stock is very favourable from a risk-reward point of view. Here also, there is a possibility that we may see a good upmove in this counter going forward.
So, many themes are playing out at this juncture. Again, the cement basket is also looking attractive. Here too, we have seen lowering of GST. The cement basket is looking promising, and stocks like UltraTech Cement, Grasim, and Ambuja Cement can all be considered.
(Disclaimer: Recommendations, suggestions, views and opinions given by the experts are their own. These do not represent the views of Economic Times)
